segments.text: What percentage of the students at UT agreed with your views, do you think?
Oh, I would say any, oh goodness, I would probably tend to estimate too high.
But there was usually a pretty sharp line drawn between, if you were associated in any way with a fraternity or sorority, first of all, you were just considered dead meat.
But those people didn't go along with it.
But that's okay because we never saw them.
They were too busy going to their little formals and semi-formals, and we were too busy making horrendous fun of them.
These were the people who wore nylons and heels and preppy-type attire at a time when most people were wearing faded jeans with holes in them and baggy shirts and no bra, so you can imagine.
But I would say probably a good...
70 to 80% of the students at the University of Texas at the time.
And that might be high, though, but it's just that everybody I knew and associated with supported it.
So it seems to me that it was high.
I'm not sure actually of the figure, though.
Why do you think SDS fell apart as a national organization?
Boy, because they started getting really violent.

And the disruptive services that we were doing were one thing, but the actual bombing of selective service offices, and of course there was a tragic accident where some SDS members were involved in making a bomb and it blew up in the basement of the home and killed three of the guys.
I guess that sort of started hitting, hey, what we're doing is really deadly.
People can really get hurt.
I mean, it's one thing to cut telephone lines to the draft board or the Selective Service Agency or to cause phone lines to go out on college campuses or just to generally harass people.
But when you start really talking about people dying and getting hurt and...
putting bombs on trains that were carrying military supplies and trying to disrupt, going onto military bases and trying to blow up arsenals and deploy or transports to Vietnam.
And even there was talk of blowing up
various senators and House of Representatives members' homes and kidnapping of children.
It just got so splintered that it became an organization.
The Weathermen became an organization of people who were really, at least for me, they wanted to do things that were much more violent than I was into.
I did not want...
I did not want to see anybody murdered or killed or seriously hurt.
I mean, if I could call someone public embarrassment and shame them or expose them for what they were doing, that was one thing.
But to actually call somebody physical or body harm, uh-uh.
That's why it fell apart for me.
Okay, what were some of the accomplishments of SDS?

Well, at the University of Texas, and that was the only place I was involved with it, I think we were very successful in making people aware that you could use more than peaceful demonstration to get your point across and that people, especially people in administrative positions, responded to...
the type of activities that I've mentioned before that we were involved in a whole lot more speedily than they did with just a whole bunch of kids sitting out on the greenways or the
or the college campuses chanting, you know, hell no, we won't go.
If you could actually get into a building and take over the dean's office or make an uproar like this, then you got the media called in.
And now the University of Texas is on national TV and parents are saying, wait a minute, we don't want our kids to go there.
So it was much more...
It brought about much quicker results and responses.
We didn't, you know, it wasn't just a bunch of, oh, aren't they sweet?
Look at those kids sitting out by the trees, singing and chanting their little anti-war songs.
Okay, well, they'll go away when they get hungry.
You know, this was, you know, let's do something else.
So I do think we brought a...
The university administration seemed to respond much more readily when they thought that damage or disruption was going to occur than if they thought it was just pure peaceful marches.
What did it mean to be a radical, or could you define a radical in the time?
Well,
I guess there were various levels of radicals, but a real radical was someone who... Jane Fonda was a radical.
She went to Hanoi.
She said she regrets it.
I think that's a political...
That was a pretty radical thing to do, to go to Hanoi and talk to the Vietnamese and take pictures smiling arm in arm with the Vietnamese.
That was radical.
To my parents, radical meant people who
shouted against the government and caused a scene.
Anybody that caused a scene.
My mother, that was her great fear that I was going to cause a scene, which I was involved in many scenes.
But that just wasn't ladylike.
A radical was somebody who
departed from what, and I guess it depends on who was calling you a radical.
That was in the eye of the beholder.
I mean, I wasn't a radical to my friends.
They felt the same way.
Somebody radical to us would have been a Green Beret or a Marine.
He was radical.
But I'm sure we were radical to him.
At the time, a radical was somebody who felt much like the people, probably, who established the original colonies and wanted to overthrow the English government.
Those were considered radicals over in the House of Parliament.
And I'm sure we were considered radicals by the powers that be here because we wanted an overthrow of the way things were being done.
What were your feelings towards Texas A&M at the time?
Those people were from another planet.
They were so out of what was going on.
They just had...
I mean, when people said Texas A&M, we envisioned...
a bunch of Marines and farmers, or a combination of the two.
People who were just so incapable of any independent thinking, who were just going to go right along.
The only solace we took in the fact was that most of them were being drafted so quickly that we knew they'd be killed.
And that perhaps all that thinking would just be slaughtered on the fields over in Vietnam.
And it was best that these people hopefully not reproduce before they left.
and leave behind widows and children who might carry on this belief.
And we truly hope that they did not think they were fighting for us because we didn't want them to fight for us.
We wanted them not to go.
We really felt that if people, if the young men just burned their death cards and said, you want to fight a war?
That politician, you go there and get it done and you fight it.
But here were these little A&M people
watching information, you know, and drilling every morning and just dying to get over there.
We waved goodbye.
When did the 60s end?
Hmm.
The 60s ended for me in 1971.
I left the United States
thinking it was for good, and went over to Israel.
And more or less just sort of deliberately lost touch.
I didn't want to know anything that was going on.
When I came back in 70, excuse me, I went over in late 1970 and came back over in 72,
When I returned to the United States, back to Austin, it was like the 60s just hadn't even existed.
People were walking to classes.
People were going to classes.
Your professors expected you in class.
It was a whole different scene.
I might add, when I went to Israel, my father felt that was the place I belonged.
My parents were not Jewish.
My husband at the time was Jewish.
So I guess I lived up to some of their expectations.
But a lot of the 60s moved what was blamed on Jews.
And it was felt that a lot of Abby Hoffman, Jerry Rubin,
And these people, that Jews were behind a lot of the black civil rights movement, too.
That the blacks were banned, or the Jewish people were standing behind the blacks in their rights movements.
And that Jews stood something to gain by claiming that the blacks were persecuted because they had been persecuted, too.
And for a long time, there was a pretty tight
between the blacks and the Jews, but I've seen that erode over the years.
Because I think the blacks realize they've been used by the Jews.
But who hasn't?
Do you consider yourself a liberated woman?
Why, yes.
Certainly more than anything else.
Could you define it?
I do not need a man to identify myself.
I do not need a man to be happy.
I am as capable of...
If someone told me I could either take
If I was going to be stranded on a desert island or a deserted island for the rest of my life and someone said, you can either take good books or a good man, I'd take the books.
I think I'd enjoy them a lot longer.
I think I wouldn't have to do any laundry or cook if I didn't feel like it.
You can use them again and again.
The older I get, the happier I am that
that somewhere along the way I distanced myself emotionally from men.
Even the most sensitive, liberated men I knew mostly gave lip service to women and their causes.
The division between the sexes, I don't think it's really narrowed that much, but I know best that

that I can, I enjoy the company of men, and I enjoy sex with men, and I'm not gay, if I were it wouldn't bother me to tell you that I was, but I'm not gay, and I do enjoy sex with men, but I think I'm able to enjoy it without wanting or needing any commitment,
I don't feel that I am bound by something that would have bound my mother, which is the sanctity of marriage.
I don't think that people are meant to be monogamous.
I don't think it's normal or natural.
I don't expect it from myself or from others.
I would never feel betrayed if the man I was with had sex with someone else.
I think that's a television and movie hype when people freak out over that.
Because I think most people who have been involved in relationships for any time know that not all of us are like Jimmy Carter and lust only in our hearts.
I'm a person who has to experience a lot of things.
I need a lot of stimuli.
And I'm not going to deny myself...
just because some religion or some social norm thinks that's what I should do.
And I guess that's what I mean by being liberated.
I do my thinking for myself.
It doesn't come out of a prayer book, and it doesn't come on the dictates of what society tells me a good woman and a good wife should be.
Did being in SDS have any impact on the increase in women's liberation?
Well, I think for me it did.
Because as I mentioned earlier, sex was a big part of the 60s.
And the men in SDS really expected as part of your deal that you would be very open sexually, you know.

In order for me to have sex with someone, I have to be attracted to that person, and I'm not going to have sex with you just because it's the thing to do that you happen to think it's the thing to do.
But even in SDS at the time, as I look back on it, women's role in the SDS was pretty much just the old vessel.
I mean, you were there to rub their backs and to...

oh you could make a few speeches you know because after all they were supposed to be open-minded and liberal but uh it was more like you were tolerated when i look back on it you were uh you were seen as a necessary evil you know yeah yeah we gotta let her speak for a while but then we can get to one of us important men they seem to be very headstrong they seem to know exactly what they wanted and
I haven't had one guy write something that he wanted me to say.
And I said, I can write my own speeches.
And he was like, no, no, no.
We don't want you to get emotional.
I just remember thinking, what in the world?
How do you feel about our government today?
Our government today?
Whose government?
How can you even use the word our?
We don't have an our government.
There is no our government.
It's still the government of the rich protecting the rich.
Our government.
Do you think our government serves women and men and blacks and Chicanos and Asians?
I mean, what a joke.
Our government.
I can hardly even deal with this question because I don't know what you mean by our government.
If you mean how do I feel about the government of the United States and comparing it with the 60s, then I don't see much change.
People have become disillusioned.
It seems like the only Kennedy left is
You know, the one they decided not to politically assassinate is the one that was the most intellectually harmless.
I don't see that.
I think it's just as corrupt and as...
When you cannot have a...
person elected to the Supreme Court of the United States because it was reported that he smoked marijuana in college.
I think that is so hypocritical that I hardly know how to deal with it.
I mean, most people are elected to government based on the amount of money they can spend in the campaign.
Our government is still a big popularity contest on a lot of levels.

name recognition most people don't even know who they vote for most people don't even vote for our government how do i feel about our government i don't feel like it's my government i don't feel like it's your government i think they've got a real good sham going i suppose but people don't really put much stock in the government sometimes i wonder who really does run the country i mean we know it's not the president
That might be interesting to explore.
What were your feelings on Richard Nixon?
Richard Nixon and I shared the same date of birth as far as January 9th went.

And every January 9th for years, my birthday was ruined by watching Nixon blow out his candles on TV while I was trying to celebrate it with my SDS and free love, free sex, free drugs society group of people.
Nixon was a jerk.
And it's just a shame that it wasn't until 1973 that the rest of the people came to know what a lying scum bucket he really was.
I sometimes wondered how all those people from A&M who went off to bleed and die for this guy felt about seeing him exposed on such a level.
Although the general sentiment of the people was Nixon hadn't done anything that anybody else hadn't done.
Nixon had only gotten caught.
So if that doesn't make more of a statement on our government, whereas people weren't really surprised that this had gone on in our Watergate, no, that's no big shock.
He hadn't done anything that wrong, but how could he be so stupid as to get caught?
Do you feel the Middle East crisis today compares with the Vietnam War, and if so, how?
Not yet, but I think that it has the potential to.
On the front page of this morning, November 17th, 1990, Houston Chronicle, there's a headline that says that major involvement in the Middle East crisis could lead to campus disrest or unrest.
And that's like a first little signal.
I thought to myself, I should cut this out and save this.
Because if it does escalate, it would be an interesting headline to keep.
I think it's there.
The problem is how much the government, our government, can convince people that our welfare is tied into our keeping the resources of the Middle East in line.
They've got us all believing that we need that Mideast oil to pollute our place.
So I guess it just depends.
We were in Vietnam strictly to keep democracy or to police the democratic process, supposedly.
We're not in the Middle East under those auspices.
We're in the Middle East to protect our oil rights.
I guess we're there for the money.
And it's the first word that we're going to be admittedly there for financial reasons alone.
This ought to be an interesting one, because the wealthy really stand to gain from this, and the poor just stand to bleed some more.
Do you think a peace movement today, if it came to that, would be possible?
I don't think so because your generation has been raised or reared on a steady diet of violence.
The TV, the movies, your music, it's extremely violent in nature.
Whereas we watch things, big movies at our time were The Endless Summer or
What was another big movie back then?
I can't even think.
Well, then the summer will do.
You've grown up on Robocop and The Avenger and Mad Max, and even your cartoons are so violent.
It's an age where we have teenagers in wealthy societies
Killing other teenagers for car stereos and where people are killed just because somebody else wants to see what it looks like to see someone die.
Or cases where during sex other people choke.
Your partner might just decide he wants to choke you to death.
See what that's like.
The drugs that you're involved in.

people are willing to take these manufactured drugs just for the high when they don't even have any idea what's in those drugs marijuana is just not enough it's you're looking for drugs that produce and by you i mean that particular generation that produce violent reactions hallucinogenic reactions that just throw your body so out of kilter and out of sync
that people don't even really realize what they're doing under the influence.
Under marijuana, you don't feel violent.
You feel laid back.
Under a lot of these acids, people get so hyper and so... People get so schizoid and freaky that... And cocaine, imagine that.
Talk about just a sheer rush high.
You can't be doing it for the effect because the effect is too short-lived.
I mean, it's not just a nice way to kick back and enjoy a Friday evening.
No, I don't think you could have a peace movement because you haven't been, you're not steeped in peace and a peaceful approach to things.
You want to blow it up, shoot it up, destroy it.

Lately with the resurgence of the Vietnam War and all of the films that were showing how the Vietnam War veteran was so maligned and mistreated, Burn on the Fourth of July, Platoon, Hamburger Hill, whatever these movies were, I think

It's also made young people today more aware of what a screwed up war that was and how we really had no place over there and even the soldiers came to believe it so that young men getting ready to go off to the Mideast today are probably going to cast a pretty jaundiced eye towards an American involvement in a place that really doesn't or who they feel we really shouldn't be.
And I don't think they will just be very content to peacefully march around and say, hell no, we won't go.
I think that's why the government's not so quick to push it.
And also the parents now of many of those people in the 60s have young sons and daughters who would be required to go.
And I think the government knows that...
The parents wouldn't support that.
I don't think people in my generation, I have a 17-year-old son, I don't want him to go.
I would advise him not to go.
And even parents, fathers or mothers who were over in Vietnam know or came to realize that that was really a war
that Americans should have stayed out of.
And they probably wouldn't want their sons over there.
So either the government's going to have to come up with another real sneaky thing like Pearl Harbor to incite American support over there, which is really a scary but not unbelievable thought.
or they're not going to have the support they need for that war.
So I think we should all be thinking right now, what are they going to do to incite us to want to go over there?
